{"title_page": "Blended threat", "text_new": "{{short description|Software exploit combining attacks against different vulnerabilities}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2018}}\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n}}\nA '''blended threat''' (also known as a '''blended attack'''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chien, Sz\u00f6r|first=Eric, P\u00e9ter|date=2002|title=Blended Attacks Exploits, Vulnerabilities and Buffer-Overflow Techniques in Computer Viruses|url=https://www.symantec.com/avcenter/reference/blended.attacks.pdf|journal=Virus Bulletin|volume=|pages=35|via=Symantec Security Response}}</ref>) is a [[software exploit]] which involves a combination of attacks against different [[vulnerability (computing)|vulnerabilities]]. Blended threats can be a combination of [[computer worm|worms]], [[trojan horse (computing)|trojan horses]], and [[computer virus|computer viruses]], all pieces of software that exploit multiple techniques to attack and propagate. A blended threat is a natural, accidental, or purposeful physical or cyber danger that has or indicates the potential to have crossover impacts and harm life, information, operations, the environment, and/or property.\n\nComplex threats consist of two or more distinct attacks aimed at a common target. These can be multiple attacks of the same kind \u2013 a series of coordinated hostilities, as seen in the Paris terrorist attacks in 2015 \u2013 or they could involve varying methods of threat, such as a cyberattack and a distinct physical attack, which may or may not be coordinated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats: Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\nIn more recent years, as cyber attacks have demonstrated increased ability to impact physical systems, such as [[Stuxnet]] and Triton<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fireeye.com/blog/threat-research/2017/12/attackers-deploy-new-ics-attack-framework-triton.html|title=Attackers Deploy New ICS Attack Framework \"TRITON\" and Cause Operational Disruption to Critical Infrastructure |website=FireEye|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> / Trisis<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dragos.com/blog/trisis/|title=TRISIS - Analyzing Safety System Targeted Malware|website=dragos.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> malware, or have caused ransomware outbreaks, such as [[WannaCry ransomware attack|WannaCry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kaspersky.com/blog/wannacry-for-b2b/16544/|title=WannaCry: What you need to know|last=Lab|first=Kaspersky|website=www.kaspersky.com|access-date=2018-02-03}}</ref> Further recognizing the threats to cyber systems that exist from potential physical hazards, the term blended threat has also been defined as a natural, accidental or purposeful physical or cyber danger that has or indicates the potential to have crossover impacts and harm life, information, operations, the environment, and/or property.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats: Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|website=gate15.global|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-update-1-1-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats (update 1.1.): Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|website=gate15.global|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref> This is an adaptation based on terminology from the 2010 US Department of Homeland Security's Risk Lexicon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dhs.gov/dhs-risk-lexicon|title=DHS Risk Lexicon|date=2009-07-06|work=Department of Homeland Security|access-date=2018-02-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn a worst case scenario, The Guardian summarized that hackers could carry out 'cyber-physical attacks,' turning satellite antennas into weapons that operate, essentially, like microwave ovens.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/reversemode?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor|title=Ruben Santamarta (@reversemode) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackhat.com/us-18/speakers/Ruben-Santamarta.html|title=Black Hat USA 2018|website=www.blackhat.com|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/news-blog/2018/aug/09/satellite-system-hacking-attacks-ships-planes-military|title=Hacked satellite systems could launch microwave-like attacks, expert warns|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=2018-08-09|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 September 2019, the Cyber Threat Alliance (CTA) released a new Joint Analysis product titled, \u201cThe Illicit Cryptocurrency Threat.\u201d Mining had become an increasing threat in that year, often assessed{{By whom|date=April 2020}} as having overtaken ransomware as the biggest cyber threat to businesses. In their summary of the threat, the CTA claimed that mining attacks had gone from almost nonexistent to being one of the most common attacks their clients encounter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyberthreatalliance.org/joint-analysis-on-illicit-cryptocurrency-mining/|title=They\u2019re Drinking Your Milkshake: CTA\u2019s Joint Analysis on Illicit Cryptocurrency Mining|date=2018-09-19|website=Cyber Threat Alliance|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\nFurther, blended threats can compromise the healthcare system. Hospitals and health care, as well as medical tools and devices, all rely on each other. Many health care systems connect to the Internet to operate, the same holds true with numerous medical devices such as pacemakers. But that makes the latter part of the \u2018Internet of Things,\u2019 a growing collection of connected devices which are potentially vulnerable to cyberattack. In fact, there have already been reports of threats to these medical devices. Just last year, the FBI recalled half a million pacemakers, as a crucial flaw was discovered that could expose users to an attack. Additionally, security researchers recently revealed a chain of vulnerabilities in a particular pacemaker brand that an attacker could exploit to control implanted pacemakers remotely and cause physical harm to patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats: Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of computer viruses and worms]]\n* [[Comparison of computer viruses]]\n* [[List of trojan horses]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mcafeeb2b.com/common/media/mcafeeb2b/us/products/pdf/wp_us_blended_threats.pdf McAfee whitepaper on blended threats][https://web.archive.org/web/20060505030819/http://www.mcafee.com/common/media/mcafeeb2b/us/products/pdf/wp_us_blended_threats.pdf]\n\n[[Category:Computer security exploits]]\n[[Category:Types of malware]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Software exploit combining attacks against different vulnerabilities}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2018}}\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n}}\nA '''blended threat''' (also known as a '''blended attack'''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chien, Sz\u00f6r|first=Eric, P\u00e9ter|date=2002|title=Blended Attacks Exploits, Vulnerabilities and Buffer-Overflow Techniques in Computer Viruses|url=https://www.symantec.com/avcenter/reference/blended.attacks.pdf|journal=Virus Bulletin|volume=|pages=35|via=Symantec Security Response}}</ref>) is a [[software exploit]] which involves a combination of attacks against different [[vulnerability (computing)|vulnerabilities]]. Blended threats can be a combination of [[computer worm|worms]], [[trojan horse (computing)|trojan horses]], and [[computer virus|computer viruses]], all pieces of software that exploit multiple techniques to attack and propagate. A blended threat is a natural, accidental, or purposeful physical or cyber danger that has or indicates the potential to have crossover impacts and harm life, information, operations, the environment, and/or property.\n\nComplex threats consist of two or more distinct attacks aimed at a common target. These can be multiple attacks of the same kind \u2013 a series of coordinated hostilities, as seen in the Paris terrorist attacks in 2015 \u2013 or they could involve varying methods of threat, such as a cyberattack and a distinct physical attack, which may or may not be coordinated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats: Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\nIn more recent years, as cyber attacks have demonstrated increased ability to impact physical systems, such as [[Stuxnet]] and Triton<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fireeye.com/blog/threat-research/2017/12/attackers-deploy-new-ics-attack-framework-triton.html|title=Attackers Deploy New ICS Attack Framework \"TRITON\" and Cause Operational Disruption to Critical Infrastructure |website=FireEye|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> / Trisis<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dragos.com/blog/trisis/|title=TRISIS - Analyzing Safety System Targeted Malware|website=dragos.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref> malware, or have caused ransomware outbreaks, such as [[WannaCry ransomware attack|WannaCry]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kaspersky.com/blog/wannacry-for-b2b/16544/|title=WannaCry: What you need to know|last=Lab|first=Kaspersky|website=www.kaspersky.com|access-date=2018-02-03}}</ref> Further recognizing the threats to cyber systems that exist from potential physical hazards, the term blended threat has also been defined as a natural, accidental or purposeful physical or cyber danger that has or indicates the potential to have crossover impacts and harm life, information, operations, the environment, and/or property.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats: Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|website=gate15.global|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-02-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-update-1-1-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats (update 1.1.): Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|website=gate15.global|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref> This is an adaptation based on terminology from the 2010 US Department of Homeland Security's Risk Lexicon.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dhs.gov/dhs-risk-lexicon|title=DHS Risk Lexicon|date=2009-07-06|work=Department of Homeland Security|access-date=2018-02-02|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn a worst case scenario, The Guardian summarized that hackers could carry out 'cyber-physical attacks', turning satellite antennas into weapons that operate, essentially, like microwave ovens.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/reversemode?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor|title=Ruben Santamarta (@reversemode) {{!}} Twitter|website=twitter.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackhat.com/us-18/speakers/Ruben-Santamarta.html|title=Black Hat USA 2018|website=www.blackhat.com|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/news-blog/2018/aug/09/satellite-system-hacking-attacks-ships-planes-military|title=Hacked satellite systems could launch microwave-like attacks, expert warns|last=Hern|first=Alex|date=2018-08-09|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 September 2019, the Cyber Threat Alliance (CTA) released a new Joint Analysis product titled, \u201cThe Illicit Cryptocurrency Threat.\u201d Mining had become an increasing threat in that year, often assessed{{By whom|date=April 2020}} as having overtaken ransomware as the biggest cyber threat to businesses. In their summary of the threat, the CTA claimed that mining attacks had gone from almost nonexistent to being one of the most common attacks their clients encounter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cyberthreatalliance.org/joint-analysis-on-illicit-cryptocurrency-mining/|title=They\u2019re Drinking Your Milkshake: CTA\u2019s Joint Analysis on Illicit Cryptocurrency Mining|date=2018-09-19|website=Cyber Threat Alliance|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\nFurther, blended threats can compromise the healthcare system. Hospitals, health care, and medical tools and devices all rely on each other. Many health care systems connect to the internet to operate, the same holds true with numerous medical devices such as pacemakers. But that makes the latter part of the \u2018Internet of Things,\u2019 a growing collection of connected devices which are potentially vulnerable to cyberattack. In fact, there have already been reports of threats to these medical devices. Just last year, the FBI recalled half a million pacemakers, as a crucial flaw was discovered that could expose users to an attack. Additionally, security researchers recently revealed a chain of vulnerabilities in a particular pacemaker brand that an attacker could exploit to control implanted pacemakers remotely and cause physical harm to patients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gate15.global/blended-threats-understanding-an-evolving-threat-environment/|title=Blended Threats: Understanding an Evolving Threat Environment|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of computer viruses and worms]]\n* [[Comparison of computer viruses]]\n* [[List of trojan horses]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.mcafeeb2b.com/common/media/mcafeeb2b/us/products/pdf/wp_us_blended_threats.pdf McAfee whitepaper on blended threats][https://web.archive.org/web/20060505030819/http://www.mcafee.com/common/media/mcafeeb2b/us/products/pdf/wp_us_blended_threats.pdf]\n\n[[Category:Computer security exploits]]\n[[Category:Types of malware]]\n", "name_user": "JDoots", "label": "safe", "comment": "various grammatical changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blended_threat"}
{"title_page": "Sekhar Kammula", "text_new": "{{Hatnote|This is a [[Telugu language|Telugu name]]; the family name is ''Kammula''.}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name  = Sekhar Kammula\n| image = Sekhar Kammula.jpg\n| occupation = Film director, producer, screenwriter\n| spouse = Sri Vidya Kammula\n| children = Vandana Kammula, Vibhav Kammula\n| awards = [[Indira Gandhi Award for Best Debut Film of a Director|National Film Award]]\n| website = {{url|http://www.sekharkammula.in}}\n| yearsactive = 1999\u2013present\n}}\n'''Kumar Sekhar Kammula''' is an [[Indian film]] director, screenwriter, actor, and producer, known for his works exclusively in [[Telugu cinema]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Sangeetha Devi Dundoo |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/article3754204.ece |title=Life & Style : Return to innocence |publisher=The Hindu |date=12 August 2012 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-12-27/news-interviews/45625585_1_film-poster-samantha-nenokkadine</ref> As a [[Master of Fine Arts]] holder from [[Howard University]], he made his directorial debut with the independent film ''[[Dollar Dreams (film)|Dollar Dreams]]'' (2000), which was a critical success, and won him the [[Indira Gandhi Award for Best First Film of a Director|National Film Award for Best First film of a director]]. The film was screened at the [[International Film Festival of India]].<ref name=\"47thawardPDF\">{{cite web|url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/47th_nff_2000.pdf|title=47th National Film Awards|format=PDF|publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]]|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> Sekhar has garnered two [[Filmfare Awards South]], and six state [[Nandi Awards]] for his works.<ref name=\"Kammula\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/thscrip/print.pl?file=2007082350180400.htm&date=2007/08/23/&prd=mp& |title=Kammula |publisher= |date= |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> Sekhar was among the director's delegation to represent [[Indian Cinema]] at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Prashanth Bhat |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-05-12/news-interviews/29532704_1_cannes-film-festival-telugu-film-nfdc |title=Sekhar Kammula at Cannes \u2013 Times of India |publisher=Articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=12 May 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis second film, ''[[Anand (2004 film)|Anand]]'', was a [[blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]] in 2004. His next film, ''[[Godavari (film)|Godavari]]'', was praised by critics and was a hit. ''[[Happy Days (2007 film)|Happy Days]]'', which was released on 28 September 2007, was declared a smash hit. It was remade in Tamil and Kannada. He was a writer for Tamil version which was released in 2010. He then directed [[Leader (2010 film)|Leader]] released on 19 February 2010 to positive reviews. In 2016, Sekhar Kammula announced his [[Bollywood]] debut with a film starring [[Salman Khan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.25cineframes.com/sekhar-kammula-bollywood-entry-with-salman-khan.html |title=Sekhar Kammula made BollyWood Entry with Salman Khan. |publisher=25cineframes.com |accessdate=30 April 2014}}</rlL0f>\n\n==Career==\nKammula graduated in Mechanical Engineering from [[Chaitanya Bharathi Institute of Technology]], completed his M.S in [[Computer science education|Computer Science]] in the U.S. He worked in the IT industry for about 3 years and then joined a film school and got his M.F.A (Film) degree at [[Howard University]], Washington D.C. During this time he worked on a number of films (short and feature length) in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |title=Telugu Cinema interview - Sekhar Kammula - Telugu film director |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/inter_sekharkammula.html |website=www.idlebrain.com |accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sekhar Kammula (Director).jpg|thumb|Sekhar Kammula in Cinivaram, Ravindra Bharathi, Hyderabad]]\n\nHe made his directorial debut with the independent film ''[[Dollar Dreams (film)|Dollar Dreams]]'' (2000), which was a critical success, and won him the [[Indira Gandhi Award for Best Debut Film of a Director|National Film Award for Best First film of a director]]. The film was screened at the [[International Film Festival of India]].<ref name=\"47thawardPDF\"/> He garnered two [[filmfare Awards South]], and six state [[Nandi Awards]] for his works.<ref name=\"Kammula\"/> Sekhar was among the director's delegation to represent [[Indian Cinema]] at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Prashanth Bhat |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-05-12/news-interviews/29532704_1_cannes-film-festival-telugu-film-nfdc |title=Sekhar Kammula at Cannes|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=12 May 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis second film, ''[[Anand (2004 film)|Anand]]'', was a [[blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]] in 2004. His next film, ''[[Godavari (film)|Godavari]]'', was praised by critics and was a hit. ''[[Happy Days (2007 film)|Happy Days]]'', which was released on 28 September 2007, was declared a smash hit. It was remade in Tamil and Kannada. He was a writer for Tamil version which was released in 2010. He then directed [[Leader (2010 film)|Leader]] released on 19 February 2010 to positive reviews. In 2016, Sekhar Kammula announced his [[Bollywood]] debut with a film starring [[Salman Khan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.25cineframes.com/sekhar-kammula-bollywood-entry-with-salman-khan.html |title=Sekhar Kammula made BollyWood Entry with Salman Khan|website=25cineframes.com |accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe directed [[Anaamika]], a Telugu remake of 2012 [[Bollywood]] hit ''[[Kahaani]]'' in which [[Nayantara]] played [[Vidya Balan]]'s character. Sekhar Kammula is going to direct his first Hindi film which is a remake of ''[[Happy Days (2007 film)|Happy Days]]''. The Hindi version will be produced by renowned film maker [[Shekhar Kapoor]]. The film will feature several new faces and Sekhar Kammula will start scouting for new faces in Mumbai and Pune, through the same process which he employed for the Telugu film. The screenplay for the film is being written by Mumbai-based writer Nikhil Mahajan.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sarah Salvadore |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-05-22/news-interviews/29568972_1_cannes-french-riviera-haobam-paban-kumar |title=Shekar calling Sekhar \u2013 Times of India |publisher=Articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=22 May 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> Shekhar Kammula's [[Fidaa]], starring [[Varun Tej]] and [[Sai Pallavi]] turned out to be a blockbuster hit with 50+ crores gross in 10 days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Varun-Tej-and-Sai-Pallavis-next-film-is-titled-Fidaa/articleshow/53556561.cms|title=Varun Tej and Sai Pallavi\u2019s next film is titled \u2018Fidaa\u2019 - Times of India|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date=2016-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10px;\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:120px;\" | Film\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10px;\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Language\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"width:200px;\"| Credited as\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:200px;\" | Notes\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\" | Writer\n! width=65 | Director\n! width=65 | Producer\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1999 || ''[[Dollar Dreams (film)|Dollar Dreams]]'' || style=\"text-align:center;\"|English, [[Telugu language|Telugu]] ||{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|Won national award in 1999. \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2004 || ''[[Anand (2004 film)|Anand]]'' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu ||{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|Also choreographer\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2006 || ''[[Godavari (film)|Godavari]]'' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu ||{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2007 || ''[[Happy Days (2007 film)|Happy Days]]'' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu ||{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|Also choreographer Won 6 Film fare Awards south in 2007 and 3 Nandi Awards. Film Fares for Best Film and Director. \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2008 || ''[[Avakai Biryani]]'' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu ||{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2010 || ''[[Leader (2010 film)|Leader]] ''||style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu||{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2012 || ''[[Life Is Beautiful (2012 film)|Life Is Beautiful]]'' ||style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu ||{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2014 || ''[[Mukunda]]'' ||style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu ||{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|{{na}}\n|[[Cameo appearance]]\n|-\n| ''[[Anamika (2013 film)|Anaamika]]'' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu, [[Tamil language|Tamil]] ||{{na}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|Also Screenplay\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2017 || ''[[Fidaa]]'' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu ||{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2020 || ''[[Love Story (2020 film)|Love Story]]'' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu ||{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|\n|\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n'''[[National Film Award (India)|National Film Award]]'''\n*[[Indira Gandhi Award for Best Debut Film of a Director]] \u2013 Golden Lotus Award \u2013 ''[[Dollar Dreams]]'' (2000)\n\n'''[[Nandi Awards]]'''\n*2004 \u2013 Nandi Award for Best Director \u2013 ''Anand''\n*2004 \u2013 Nandi Award for Second Best Feature Film \u2013 ''[[Anand (2004 film)|Anand]]''\n*2006 -  Nandi Award for Second Best Feature Film \u2013 ''Godavari''\n*2006 \u2013 [[Nandi Award for Best Director]] \u2013 ''Godavari''\n*2007 \u2013 [[Nandi Award for Second Best Feature Film]] \u2013 ''[[Happy Days (2007 film)|Happy Days]]''\n*2011 \u2013 Nandi Award for Best Story \u2013 ''[[Leader (2010 film)|Leader]]''\n\n'''[[Filmfare Awards South]]'''\n*2007 \u2013 [[Filmfare Best Film Award (Telugu)]] \u2013 ''[[Happy Days (2007 film)|Happy Days]]''\n*2007 \u2013 [[Filmfare Best Director Award (Telugu)]] \u2013 ''Happy Days''\n\n'''Other awards'''\n*Dasari Best Film Director Award \u2013 ''[[Happy Days (2007 film)|Happy Days]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/thscrip/print.pl?file=2008050559710400.htm&date=2008/05/05/&prd=th& |title=Happy Days |publisher= |date= |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>\n*Zee Golden Awards 2017 - Best Director \u2013 ''[[Fidaa]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=2289322|name=Sekhar Kammula}}\n*http://www.amigoscreations.com/\n\n{{Sekhar Kammula}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestTeluguDirector}}\n{{Nandi Award for Best Director}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kammula, Shekhar}}\n[[Category:21st-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Telugu film directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Howard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University alumni]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards South winners]]\n[[Category:Nandi Award winners]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Telugu screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Telugu film producers]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Director whose film won the Best Debut Feature Film National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Producers who won the Best Debut Feature Film of a Director National Film Award]]\n", "text_old": "{{Hatnote|This is a [[Telugu language|Telugu name]]; the family name is ''Kammula''.}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name  = Sekhar Kammula\n| image = Sekhar Kammula.jpg\n| occupation = Film director, producer, screenwriter\n| spouse = Sri Vidya Kammula\n| children = Vandana Kammula, Vibhav Kammula\n| awards = [[Indira Gandhi Award for Best Debut Film of a Director|National Film Award]]\n| website = {{url|http://www.sekharkammula.in}}\n| yearsactive = 1999\u2013present\n}}\n'''Kumar Sekhar Kammula''' is an [[Indian film]] director, screenwriter, actor, and producer, known for his works exclusively in [[Telugu cinema]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Sangeetha Devi Dundoo |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/article3754204.ece |title=Life & Style : Return to innocence |publisher=The Hindu |date=12 August 2012 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref><ref>http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-12-27/news-interviews/45625585_1_film-poster-samantha-nenokkadine</ref> As a [[Master of Fine Arts]] holder from [[Howard University]], he made his directorial debut with the independent film ''[[Dollar Dreams (film)|Dollar Dreams]]'' (2000), which was a critical success, and won him the [[Indira Gandhi Award for Best First Film of a Director|National Film Award for Best First film of a director]]. The film was screened at the [[International Film Festival of India]].<ref name=\"47thawardPDF\">{{cite web|url=http://dff.nic.in/2011/47th_nff_2000.pdf|title=47th National Film Awards|format=PDF|publisher=[[Directorate of Film Festivals]]|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> Sekhar has garnered two [[Filmfare Awards South]], and six state [[Nandi Awards]] for his works.<ref name=\"Kammula\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/thehindu/thscrip/print.pl?file=2007082350180400.htm&date=2007/08/23/&prd=mp& |title=Kammula |publisher= |date= |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> Sekhar was among the director's delegation to represent [[Indian Cinema]] at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Prashanth Bhat |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-05-12/news-interviews/29532704_1_cannes-film-festival-telugu-film-nfdc |title=Sekhar Kammula at Cannes \u2013 Times of India |publisher=Articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=12 May 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis second film, ''[[Anand (2004 film)|Anand]]'', was a [[blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]] in 2004. His next film, ''[[Godavari (film)|Godavari]]'', was praised by critics and was a hit. ''[[Happy Days (2007 film)|Happy Days]]'', which was released on 28 September 2007, was declared a smash hit. It was remade in Tamil and Kannada. He was a writer for Tamil version which was released in 2010. He then directed [[Leader (2010 film)|Leader]] released on 19 February 2010 to positive reviews. In 2016, Sekhar Kammula announced his [[Bollywood]] debut with a film starring [[Salman Khan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.25cineframes.com/sekhar-kammula-bollywood-entry-with-salman-khan.html |title=Sekhar Kammula made BollyWood Entry with Salman Khan. |publisher=25cineframes.com |accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKammula graduated in Mechanical Engineering from [[Chaitanya Bharathi Institute of Technology]], completed his M.S in [[Computer science education|Computer Science]] in the U.S. He worked in the IT industry for about 3 years and then joined a film school and got his M.F.A (Film) degree at [[Howard University]], Washington D.C. During this time he worked on a number of films (short and feature length) in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |title=Telugu Cinema interview - Sekhar Kammula - Telugu film director |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/inter_sekharkammula.html |website=www.idlebrain.com |accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sekhar Kammula (Director).jpg|thumb|Sekhar Kammula in Cinivaram, Ravindra Bharathi, Hyderabad]]\n\nHe made his directorial debut with the independent film ''[[Dollar Dreams (film)|Dollar Dreams]]'' (2000), which was a critical success, and won him the [[Indira Gandhi Award for Best Debut Film of a Director|National Film Award for Best First film of a director]]. The film was screened at the [[International Film Festival of India]].<ref name=\"47thawardPDF\"/> He garnered two [[filmfare Awards South]], and six state [[Nandi Awards]] for his works.<ref name=\"Kammula\"/> Sekhar was among the director's delegation to represent [[Indian Cinema]] at the [[2011 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Prashanth Bhat |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-05-12/news-interviews/29532704_1_cannes-film-festival-telugu-film-nfdc |title=Sekhar Kammula at Cannes|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=12 May 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis second film, ''[[Anand (2004 film)|Anand]]'', was a [[blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]] in 2004. His next film, ''[[Godavari (film)|Godavari]]'', was praised by critics and was a hit. ''[[Happy Days (2007 film)|Happy Days]]'', which was released on 28 September 2007, was declared a smash hit. It was remade in Tamil and Kannada. He was a writer for Tamil version which was released in 2010. He then directed [[Leader (2010 film)|Leader]] released on 19 February 2010 to positive reviews. In 2016, Sekhar Kammula announced his [[Bollywood]] debut with a film starring [[Salman Khan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.25cineframes.com/sekhar-kammula-bollywood-entry-with-salman-khan.html |title=Sekhar Kammula made BollyWood Entry with Salman Khan|website=25cineframes.com |accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe directed [[Anaamika]], a Telugu remake of 2012 [[Bollywood]] hit ''[[Kahaani]]'' in which [[Nayantara]] played [[Vidya Balan]]'s character. Sekhar Kammula is going to direct his first Hindi film which is a remake of ''[[Happy Days (2007 film)|Happy Days]]''. The Hindi version will be produced by renowned film maker [[Shekhar Kapoor]]. The film will feature several new faces and Sekhar Kammula will start scouting for new faces in Mumbai and Pune, through the same process which he employed for the Telugu film. The screenplay for the film is being written by Mumbai-based writer Nikhil Mahajan.<ref>{{cite news|author=Sarah Salvadore |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-05-22/news-interviews/29568972_1_cannes-french-riviera-haobam-paban-kumar |title=Shekar calling Sekhar \u2013 Times of India |publisher=Articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=22 May 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> Shekhar Kammula's [[Fidaa]], starring [[Varun Tej]] and [[Sai Pallavi]] turned out to be a blockbuster hit with 50+ crores gross in 10 days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Varun-Tej-and-Sai-Pallavis-next-film-is-titled-Fidaa/articleshow/53556561.cms|title=Varun Tej and Sai Pallavi\u2019s next film is titled \u2018Fidaa\u2019 - Times of India|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date=2016-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10px;\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:120px;\" | Film\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10px;\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Language\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"width:200px;\"| Credited as\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:200px;\" | Notes\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\" | Writer\n! width=65 | Director\n! width=65 | Producer\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1999 || ''[[Dollar Dreams (film)|Dollar Dreams]]'' || style=\"text-align:center;\"|English, [[Telugu language|Telugu]] ||{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|Won national award in 1999. \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2004 || ''[[Anand (2004 film)|Anand]]'' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu ||{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|Also choreographer\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2006 || ''[[Godavari (film)|Godavari]]'' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu ||{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{na}}\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2007 || ''[[Happy Days (2007 film)|Happy Days]]'' || style=\"text-align:center;\"| Telugu ||{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|{{ya}}\n|Also choreographer Won 6 Film fare Awards south in 2007 and 3 Nandi Awards. Film Fares for Best Film and Director. \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:ce