{"title_page": "Antonio Crutta", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Crutta \u0141ukasz Antoni or Antonio Crutta\n| image         = Portrait of Crutta \u0141ukasz Antoni in 1779.jpg\n| caption       = Crutta \u0141ukasz Antoni or Antonio Crutta\n| birth_name    = Antonio Crutta\n| birth_date    = 1727\n| birth_place   = Cyprus (Venice)\n| death_date    = 1812-14\n| death_place   = Lewiczyn\n| nationality   = Venetian\n| other_names   = Antonio Kruta, Antoine Crutta, Antoni Crutta\n| occupation    = Translator, advisor and diplomat.\n| years_active  = ca. 1747-1811-12\n| known_for     = Speaking 9 languages\n}}\n\n'''Antonio Crutta''' ([[Polish language|Polish]]: ''Crutta \u0141ukasz Antoni'') ([[Albanian language|Alb]]. ''Antonio Kruta'') (b. 1727, Cyprus (Venice) - d. Lewiczyn, 1812-1814) was a translator, politician, [[dragoman]] and diplomat of Venetian background, originating from the Albanian [[Kryethi|Kruta]] (Kryethi or Kruotta) tribe. His father was Albanian and his mother Italian.<ref>{{cite web |title=Collection of Royal Castle in Warsaw - Antoni \u0141ukasz Crutta. ( Antoni \u0141ukasz Crutta Signed and dated bottom left: Duch\u00e2teau/ Pinxit/ 1779 (the last digit is barely visible).  Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Duch\u00e2teau (d. after 1796); French painter active in Istanbul and connected with the diplomatic corps.  Antoni \u0141ukasz Crutta (1727\u20131812), was born in Cyprus. The son on an Albanian father and Italian mother, he was clerk and translator/interpreter to the Venetian consulate in Larnaca. From 1765 he was in the service of Stanis\u0142aw August as translator of oriental languages; he was made a nobleman in 1775.  Pendant to the portrait of his wife (ZKW/722/ab). |url=https://kolekcja.zamek-krolewski.pl/en/obiekt/id/ZKW_721_ab |website=kolekcja.zamek-krolewski.pl}}</ref> The family has established themselves in [[Pera (Beyo\u011flu)|Pera]] since 1693. Antoine, Antonio or Antoni served as interpreter and translator of King [[Stanis\u0142aw August Poniatowski]] during the [[Russo-Turkish War (1787\u20131792)|Russo-Turkish war]] 1787 in Poland.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Reychman |first1=Jan |last2=Zajaczkowski |first2=Ananiasz |title=Handbook of Ottoman-Turkish Diplomatics |date=2014 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG |isbn=978-3-11-081269-5 |page=20 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=oEZbDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=Crutta+Albanian&source=bl&ots=N9pRyzBM2l&sig=ACfU3U0lnS1-diLVaqYk4w47_rGTrqrCRw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiSscTxycLoAhW9xMQBHV-DCvcQ6AEwAXoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=Crutta&f=false |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Roland |first1=Ruth A. |title=Interpreters as Diplomats: A Diplomatic History of the Role of Interpreters in World Politics |date=1999 |publisher=University of Ottawa Press |isbn=978-0-7766-0501-2 |page=[https://archive.org/details/interpretersasdi0000rola/page/49 49] |url=https://archive.org/details/interpretersasdi0000rola |url-access=registration |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> He spoke 9 languages. In 1792, Antonio did such a good job at keeping the peace between Poland and the Ottomans that he was conferred a title of nobility. Antonios brother Pierre, and his son Jean, followed in the same tracks, and worked in Istanbul, trying to persuade the French to help the Polacks form an alliance. He received an English passport by the English ambassador in Warsaw and travelled to Constantinople where he met French diplomat [[Marie Louis Descorches]]. However [[Tadeusz Ko\u015bciuszko]], who had sent Pierre on the mission, was overthrown and Pierre remained in Istanbul until he died in 1797. The family was known to serve Russian, French, English, Polish and Venetian embassies.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gelder |first1=G. J. H. van |last2=Moor |first2=Ed de |title=Eastward Bound: Dutch Ventures and Adventures in the Middle East |date=1994 |publisher=Rodopi |isbn=978-90-5183-717-9 |page=138 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=jDNB294N7AcC&pg=PA133&lpg=PA133&dq=Catholic+Fandi+Ottoman+Empire&source=bl&ots=npd_ZniHGX&sig=ACfU3U0CUPpFIwbbp3RzqvSoodPdJaRFzw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjpjKWDx8LoAhVlycQBHSHXDH8Q6AEwF3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Albanian&f=false |language=en}}</ref> Another member of the family titled \"''Doctor Crutta''\" or \"''Signor Crutta''\" is mentioned as a dragoman and chancellor in service of the British embassy between 1745 and 1764 in the European colony of [[Larnaca]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Drummond |first1=Alexander |title=Travels Through Different Cities of Germany, Italy, Greece and Several Parts of Asia, as the Far as the Banks of the Euphrates, in a Series of Letters... by Alexander Drummond,... |date=1754 |publisher=The autor |page=[https://archive.org/details/travelsthroughdi00drum/page/280 280] |url=https://archive.org/details/travelsthroughdi00drum |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Kitromilides |first1=Paschalis |title=Insular Destinies: Perspectives on the history and politics of modern Cyprus |date=2019 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-351-12780-6 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=yaS-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT63&dq=Crutta&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwippe-GisXoAhVBw4sKHciKAm8Q6AEISjAE#v=onepage&q=Crutta&f=false |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Life and family ==\n\nAntonio entered early in the service of Poland on January 1, 1748, as the chancellor of the [[Republic of Venice]] in [[Larnaca]] in Cyprus. He worked there until 1765 when he arrived through the British ambassador to Constantinople to transmit his offers to the King of Poland. Descorches and Crutta worked to withdraw the Ottoman Empire from war in order to maintain the peace with Poland, but due to the insurrection, their work was useless. Crutta also asked the Royalty to pay off his old debts which he had acquired in Cyprus and Istanbul and the Polish king paid 23 ducats a month, but it was not satiable to Crutta who complained.<ref>{{cite book |title=Polish archives of oriental research |date=1961 |publisher=Pa\u0144stwowe Wydawn. Naukowe. |pages=85\u201388, 93 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=-LviAAAAMAAJ&q=Crutta&dq=Crutta&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwippe-GisXoAhVBw4sKHciKAm8Q6AEIaDAI |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=fr}}</ref>\n\nAntonio also served the British embassy under [[John Murray (British diplomat)|John Murray]], as one of its many \"Levantine\" (Catholic and able to speak Italian) translators.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F7Q4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=Antonio+Crutta&source=bl&ots=h6WRjZgywv&sig=ACfU3U2c2ejQbN4eCm8GxUj0vzazUy1Cjw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjllLiTucroAhXDBc0KHSjcDo0Q6AEwBHoECAsQNA#v=onepage&q=Antonio%20Crutta&f=false|page=152|title=British-Ottoman Relations, 1661-1807: Commerce and Diplomatic Practice in Eighteenth-century Istanbul|author=Michael Tarbot|date=2017|publisher=Boydell & Brewer}}</ref>\n\nAntonios brother, Joseph Crutta, was also a dragoman for the Russian embassy in Istanbul. He spent several years in prison in the [[Ch\u00e2teau des Tours|Ch\u00e2teau des Sept Tours]] together with Russian ambassador [[Nikolai Vasilyeich Repnin|Vasily Repnin]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Deutsche Akademie der Wissenschaften zu Berlin. Institut f\u00fcr Griechisch-R\u00f6mische Altertumskunde, Deutsche Akademie der Wissenschaften zu Berlin. Zentralinstitut f\u00fcr Alte Geschichte und Arch\u00e4ologie, Universit\u00e4t Halle-Wittenberg. Sektion Orient- und Altertumswissenschaften |date=168 |publisher=Akademie-Verlag |location=University of Michigan |page=308 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=G0ZoAAAAMAAJ&q=Joseph+Crutta&dq=Joseph+Crutta&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzqMD1jsXoAhXwlIsKHWX9D3IQ6AEILzAB |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Ward |first1=Sir Adolphus William |title=The Cambridge Modern History |date=1907 |publisher=CUP Archive |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=Bao8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA1009&lpg=PA1009&dq=Nicholas+Bepnin&source=bl&ots=dagkCm3cnz&sig=ACfU3U29fqY22gmgZcChoIsuWuOx_N2gwQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiykqrBj8XoAhXhwqYKHQ8sCEoQ6AEwA3oECAUQAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> There exists a well-known portrait of Antoine Crutta, painted by Canaletto, representing the election of King Stanis\u0142aw August Poniatowski in 1764. Joseph Crutta wanted to stay in Istanbul and work as the Russian consul as the Russian climate could prove fatal.<ref>{{cite book |title=Archives polonaises d'etudes orientales |date=1961 |publisher=Towarzystwo |pages=96\u201397 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=PuMNAAAAYAAJ&q=Joseph+Crutta&dq=Joseph+Crutta&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzqMD1jsXoAhXwlIsKHWX9D3IQ6AEIODAC |language=fr}}</ref> Joseph Crutta apparently died in 1780 from drug abuse and so did his brother Alexander Crutta.<ref>{{cite book |title=Actes |date=1959 |pages=609\u2013611 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=3qhMAAAAYAAJ&dq=Joseph+Crutta&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=1780 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAntonio Crutta was also a politician and translator of Oriental languages. He lived in Lewiczyn in the Belsk Du\u017cy commune. The Poles called him \"''Albanian Antoni Lukasz Crutta''\" and he was a cherished dragoman of the Byzantine and Middle East. He was also a guide and intermediary between foriengers and inhabitants of the Orient. Prior to his service to Stanislav, Crutta had served in the Court of Venice in Cyprus. He spoke Latin, Greek, French, English, Italian, Armenian, Turkish, Tatar and Persian.<ref>{{cite news |title=Crutta \u0141ukasz Antoni - Gmina Belsk Du\u017cy |url=http://www.belskduzy.pl/info/zawartosc/114/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=www.belskduzy.pl |agency=Belskduzy commune |issue=Life and death of Crutta \u0141ukasz Antoni}}</ref> In 1777, he accompanied MP Numanbey, representing the Ottoman Sultan, and translating Treaty Documents. The Polish royalty of [[Rzeczpospolita]] gave Crutta the title of nobility. At old age, he settled in Lewiczyn, belonging to his son-in-law, daughter of Antoni Crutta. He lived in property owned by Wojciech Piotr Bedli\u0144ski. Antoni died in 1727, and all three are buried in the church yard at the temple of Lewiczyn.\n\n== Depiction in painting ==\n[[File:Bellotto Election of Stanislas Augustus.jpg|thumb|\"L\u2019\u00c9LECTION DE STANISLAS AUGUSTE\n(1778)\". \"Election of Stanislas Augustus\", painted by Italian painter [[Bernardo Bellotto]] first in 1776, which was given to court marshal Francizsek Rzewuski. The painting currently in the Poznan National Museum.  A second one was painted in 1778 with more details. The painting depicts the election of 1764, September 7, outside of Warsaw, now a district of the capital. According to museum exhibition curator Stephane Loire, curator from the Painting Department of the Louvre Museum Andrzej Rottermund and curator at the Royal Ch\u00e2teau in Varsovie Hanna Malachowicz, Antonio Crutta is depicted at the far right, standing in front of Bellotto with his three daughters.]]\n\nAntonio is depicted in Bernardo Bellotto's painting \"Election of Stanislas Augustus\" from 1776 and 1778. Mieczyslaw Wallis describes him as following:\n''\"Standing in front of the tent, a stout grand man, deed in a fur cap and blue coat, in floral zupper and red greyhounds with a dagger stuck behind his belt, looking through the magnifying glass of the election, an expert in Eastern languages and head office of the Crown Chancellery, Antoni \u0141ukasz Crutta (1725-1812), Albanian, or more specifically Italian, Albanian, probably a Venetian citizen who arrived in 1765 Warsaw, in 1775 he obtained an indigenate, and on February 26, 1778 he received the title of consistory officer in foreign countries\"''.<ref>{{cite book |title=Pa\u0144stwowy Instytut Sztuki [Hrsg.]; Stowarzyszenie Historyk\u00f3w Sztuki [Hrsg.]: Biuletyn Historii Sztuki (16.1954) |url=https://digi.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/diglit/bhs1954/0144/text_ocr |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=RFI partenaire de l\u2019exposition \u201cBernardo Bellotto. Tableaux du Ch\u00e2teau Royal de Varsovie\u201d et du cycle \u201cIdentit\u00e9s polonaises : patrimoine et cr\u00e9ation \u00e0 l\u2019auditorium du Louvre\u201d |publisher=www.louvre.fr. |edition=On the right, at the very edge of the painting, we can see Bellotto in profile, in a tent, seated at a table with his three daughters as well as, standing before them, Antoni Lukasz Crutta, the king's translator for languages oriental. |url=https://www.louvre.fr/sites/default/files/medias/medias_fichiers/fichiers/pdf/louvre-dossier-presse-bellotto.pdf |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crutta, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1814 deaths]]\n[[Category:Albanian diplomats]]\n[[Category:Albanian spies]]\n[[Category:1727 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Crutta \u0141ukasz Antoni or Antonio Crutta\n| image         = Portrait of Crutta \u0141ukasz Antoni in 1779.jpg\n| caption       = Crutta \u0141ukasz Antoni or Antonio Crutta\n| birth_name    = Antonio Crutta\n| birth_date    = 1727\n| birth_place   = Cyprus (Venice)\n| death_date    = 1812-14\n| death_place   = Lewiczyn\n| nationality   = Venetian\n| other_names   = Antonio Kruta, Antoine Crutta, Antoni Crutta\n| occupation    = Translator, advisor and diplomat.\n| years_active  = ca. 1747-1811-12\n| known_for     = Speaking 9 languages\n}}\n\n'''Antonio Crutta''' ([[Polish language|Polish]]: ''Crutta \u0141ukasz Antoni'') ([[Albanian language|Alb]]. ''Antonio Kruta'') (b. 1727, Cyprus (Venice) - d. Lewiczyn, 1812-1814) was a translator, politician, [[dragoman]] and diplomat of Venetian background, originating from the Albanian [[Kryethi|Kruta]] (Kryethi or Kruotta) tribe. His father was Albanian and his mother Italian.<ref>{{cite web |title=Collection of Royal Castle in Warsaw - Antoni \u0141ukasz Crutta. ( Antoni \u0141ukasz Crutta Signed and dated bottom left: Duch\u00e2teau/ Pinxit/ 1779 (the last digit is barely visible).  Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Duch\u00e2teau (d. after 1796); French painter active in Istanbul and connected with the diplomatic corps.  Antoni \u0141ukasz Crutta (1727\u20131812), was born in Cyprus. The son on an Albanian father and Italian mother, he was clerk and translator/interpreter to the Venetian consulate in Larnaca. From 1765 he was in the service of Stanis\u0142aw August as translator of oriental languages; he was made a nobleman in 1775.  Pendant to the portrait of his wife (ZKW/722/ab). |url=https://kolekcja.zamek-krolewski.pl/en/obiekt/id/ZKW_721_ab |website=kolekcja.zamek-krolewski.pl}}</ref> The family has established themselves in [[Pera (Beyo\u011flu)|Pera]] since 1693. Antoine, Antonio or Antoni served as interpreter and translator of King [[Stanis\u0142aw August Poniatowski]] during the [[Russo-Turkish War (1787\u20131792)|Russo-Turkish war]] 1787 in Poland.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Reychman |first1=Jan |last2=Zajaczkowski |first2=Ananiasz |title=Handbook of Ottoman-Turkish Diplomatics |date=2014 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG |isbn=978-3-11-081269-5 |page=20 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=oEZbDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA20&lpg=PA20&dq=Crutta+Albanian&source=bl&ots=N9pRyzBM2l&sig=ACfU3U0lnS1-diLVaqYk4w47_rGTrqrCRw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiSscTxycLoAhW9xMQBHV-DCvcQ6AEwAXoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=Crutta&f=false |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Roland |first1=Ruth A. |title=Interpreters as Diplomats: A Diplomatic History of the Role of Interpreters in World Politics |date=1999 |publisher=University of Ottawa Press |isbn=978-0-7766-0501-2 |page=[https://archive.org/details/interpretersasdi0000rola/page/49 49] |url=https://archive.org/details/interpretersasdi0000rola |url-access=registration |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> He spoke 9 languages. In 1792, Antonio did such a good job at keeping the peace between Poland and the Ottomans that he was conferred a title of nobility. Antonios brother Pierre, and his son Jean, followed in the same tracks, and worked in Istanbul, trying to persuade the French to help the Polacks form an alliance. He received an English passport by the English ambassador in Warsaw and travelled to Constantinople where he met French diplomat [[Marie Louis Descorches]]. However [[Tadeusz Ko\u015bciuszko]], who had sent Pierre on the mission, was overthrown and Pierre remained in Istanbul until he died in 1797. The family was known to serve Russian, French, English, Polish and Venetian embassies.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gelder |first1=G. J. H. van |last2=Moor |first2=Ed de |title=Eastward Bound: Dutch Ventures and Adventures in the Middle East |date=1994 |publisher=Rodopi |isbn=978-90-5183-717-9 |page=138 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=jDNB294N7AcC&pg=PA133&lpg=PA133&dq=Catholic+Fandi+Ottoman+Empire&source=bl&ots=npd_ZniHGX&sig=ACfU3U0CUPpFIwbbp3RzqvSoodPdJaRFzw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjpjKWDx8LoAhVlycQBHSHXDH8Q6AEwF3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=Albanian&f=false |language=en}}</ref> Another member of the family titled \"''Doctor Crutta''\" or \"''Signor Crutta''\" is mentioned as a dragoman and chancellor in service of the British embassy between 1745 and 1764 in the European colony of [[Larnaca]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Drummond |first1=Alexander |title=Travels Through Different Cities of Germany, Italy, Greece and Several Parts of Asia, as the Far as the Banks of the Euphrates, in a Series of Letters... by Alexander Drummond,... |date=1754 |publisher=The autor |page=[https://archive.org/details/travelsthroughdi00drum/page/280 280] |url=https://archive.org/details/travelsthroughdi00drum |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Kitromilides |first1=Paschalis |title=Insular Destinies: Perspectives on the history and politics of modern Cyprus |date=2019 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-351-12780-6 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=yaS-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT63&dq=Crutta&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwippe-GisXoAhVBw4sKHciKAm8Q6AEISjAE#v=onepage&q=Crutta&f=false |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Life and family ==\n\nAntonio entered early in the service of Poland on January 1, 1748, as the chancellor of the [[Republic of Venice]] in [[Larnaca]] in Cyprus. He worked there until 1765 when he arrived through the British ambassador to Constantinople to transmit his offers to the King of Poland. Descorches and Crutta worked to withdraw the Ottoman Empire from war in order to maintain the peace with Poland, but due to the insurrection, their work was useless. Crutta also asked the Royalty to pay off his old debts which he had acquired in Cyprus and Istanbul and the Polish king paid 23 ducats a month, but it was not satiable to Crutta who complained.<ref>{{cite book |title=Polish archives of oriental research |date=1961 |publisher=Pa\u0144stwowe Wydawn. Naukowe. |pages=85\u201388, 93 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=-LviAAAAMAAJ&q=Crutta&dq=Crutta&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwippe-GisXoAhVBw4sKHciKAm8Q6AEIaDAI |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=fr}}</ref>\n\nAntonio also served the British embassy under [[John Murray]], as one of its many \"Levantine\" (Catholic and able to speak Italian) translators.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F7Q4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA152&lpg=PA152&dq=Antonio+Crutta&source=bl&ots=h6WRjZgywv&sig=ACfU3U2c2ejQbN4eCm8GxUj0vzazUy1Cjw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjllLiTucroAhXDBc0KHSjcDo0Q6AEwBHoECAsQNA#v=onepage&q=Antonio%20Crutta&f=false|page=152|title=British-Ottoman Relations, 1661-1807: Commerce and Diplomatic Practice in Eighteenth-century Istanbul|author=Michael Tarbot|date=2017|publisher=Boydell & Brewer}}</ref>\n\nAntonios brother, Joseph Crutta, was also a dragoman for the Russian embassy in Istanbul. He spent several years in prison in the [[Ch\u00e2teau des Tours|Ch\u00e2teau des Sept Tours]] together with Russian ambassador [[Nikolai Vasilyeich Repnin|Vasily Repnin]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Deutsche Akademie der Wissenschaften zu Berlin. Institut f\u00fcr Griechisch-R\u00f6mische Altertumskunde, Deutsche Akademie der Wissenschaften zu Berlin. Zentralinstitut f\u00fcr Alte Geschichte und Arch\u00e4ologie, Universit\u00e4t Halle-Wittenberg. Sektion Orient- und Altertumswissenschaften |date=168 |publisher=Akademie-Verlag |location=University of Michigan |page=308 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=G0ZoAAAAMAAJ&q=Joseph+Crutta&dq=Joseph+Crutta&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzqMD1jsXoAhXwlIsKHWX9D3IQ6AEILzAB |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Ward |first1=Sir Adolphus William |title=The Cambridge Modern History |date=1907 |publisher=CUP Archive |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=Bao8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA1009&lpg=PA1009&dq=Nicholas+Bepnin&source=bl&ots=dagkCm3cnz&sig=ACfU3U29fqY22gmgZcChoIsuWuOx_N2gwQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiykqrBj8XoAhXhwqYKHQ8sCEoQ6AEwA3oECAUQAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> There exists a well-known portrait of Antoine Crutta, painted by Canaletto, representing the election of King Stanis\u0142aw August Poniatowski in 1764. Joseph Crutta wanted to stay in Istanbul and work as the Russian consul as the Russian climate could prove fatal.<ref>{{cite book |title=Archives polonaises d'etudes orientales |date=1961 |publisher=Towarzystwo |pages=96\u201397 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=PuMNAAAAYAAJ&q=Joseph+Crutta&dq=Joseph+Crutta&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzqMD1jsXoAhXwlIsKHWX9D3IQ6AEIODAC |language=fr}}</ref> Joseph Crutta apparently died in 1780 from drug abuse and so did his brother Alexander Crutta.<ref>{{cite book |title=Actes |date=1959 |pages=609\u2013611 |url=https://books.google.se/books?id=3qhMAAAAYAAJ&dq=Joseph+Crutta&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=1780 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAntonio Crutta was also a politician and translator of Oriental languages. He lived in Lewiczyn in the Belsk Du\u017cy commune. The Poles called him \"''Albanian Antoni Lukasz Crutta''\" and he was a cherished dragoman of the Byzantine and Middle East. He was also a guide and intermediary between foriengers and inhabitants of the Orient. Prior to his service to Stanislav, Crutta had served in the Court of Venice in Cyprus. He spoke Latin, Greek, French, English, Italian, Armenian, Turkish, Tatar and Persian.<ref>{{cite news |title=Crutta \u0141ukasz Antoni - Gmina Belsk Du\u017cy |url=http://www.belskduzy.pl/info/zawartosc/114/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=www.belskduzy.pl |agency=Belskduzy commune |issue=Life and death of Crutta \u0141ukasz Antoni}}</ref> In 1777, he accompanied MP Numanbey, representing the Ottoman Sultan, and translating Treaty Documents. The Polish royalty of [[Rzeczpospolita]] gave Crutta the title of nobility. At old age, he settled in Lewiczyn, belonging to his son-in-law, daughter of Antoni Crutta. He lived in property owned by Wojciech Piotr Bedli\u0144ski. Antoni died in 1727, and all three are buried in the church yard at the temple of Lewiczyn.\n\n== Depiction in painting ==\n[[File:Bellotto Election of Stanislas Augustus.jpg|thumb|\"L\u2019\u00c9LECTION DE STANISLAS AUGUSTE\n(1778)\". \"Election of Stanislas Augustus\", painted by Italian painter [[Bernardo Bellotto]] first in 1776, which was given to court marshal Francizsek Rzewuski. The painting currently in the Poznan National Museum.  A second one was painted in 1778 with more details. The painting depicts the election of 1764, September 7, outside of Warsaw, now a district of the capital. According to museum exhibition curator Stephane Loire, curator from the Painting Department of the Louvre Museum Andrzej Rottermund and curator at the Royal Ch\u00e2teau in Varsovie Hanna Malachowicz, Antonio Crutta is depicted at the far right, standing in front of Bellotto with his three daughters.]]\n\nAntonio is depicted in Bernardo Bellotto's painting \"Election of Stanislas Augustus\" from 1776 and 1778. Mieczyslaw Wallis describes him as following:\n''\"Standing in front of the tent, a stout grand man, deed in a fur cap and blue coat, in floral zupper and red greyhounds with a dagger stuck behind his belt, looking through the magnifying glass of the election, an expert in Eastern languages and head office of the Crown Chancellery, Antoni \u0141ukasz Crutta (1725-1812), Albanian, or more specifically Italian, Albanian, probably a Venetian citizen who arrived in 1765 Warsaw, in 1775 he obtained an indigenate, and on February 26, 1778 he received the title of consistory officer in foreign countries\"''.<ref>{{cite book |title=Pa\u0144stwowy Instytut Sztuki [Hrsg.]; Stowarzyszenie Historyk\u00f3w Sztuki [Hrsg.]: Biuletyn Historii Sztuki (16.1954) |url=https://digi.ub.uni-heidelberg.de/diglit/bhs1954/0144/text_ocr |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=de}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=RFI partenaire de l\u2019exposition \u201cBernardo Bellotto. Tableaux du Ch\u00e2teau Royal de Varsovie\u201d et du cycle \u201cIdentit\u00e9s polonaises : patrimoine et cr\u00e9ation \u00e0 l\u2019auditorium du Louvre\u201d |publisher=www.louvre.fr. |edition=On the right, at the very edge of the painting, we can see Bellotto in profile, in a tent, seated at a table with his three daughters as well as, standing before them, Antoni Lukasz Crutta, the king's translator for languages oriental. |url=https://www.louvre.fr/sites/default/files/medias/medias_fichiers/fichiers/pdf/louvre-dossier-presse-bellotto.pdf |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crutta, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1814 deaths]]\n[[Category:Albanian diplomats]]\n[[Category:Albanian spies]]\n[[Category:1727 births]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJohn Murray(link changed toJohn Murray (British diplomat)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antonio_Crutta"}
{"title_page": "The Mountain Bard", "text_new": "'''The Mountain Bard''' (1807), containing 21 poems, was [[James Hogg]]'s first substantial poetical publication.\n\n==Editions==\n===The first edition===\n''The Mountain Bard; consisting of Ballads and Songs, founded on facts and legendary tales. By James Hogg, The Ettrick Shepherd'' was first published in Edinburgh in February 1807 by [[Archibald Constable]] and Co. and in London by [[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]].<ref>James Hogg, ''The Mountain Bard'', ed. Suzanne Gilbert (Edinburgh, 2007), xli. </ref> Hogg had had seven poems printed privately in 1801 as ''Scottish Pastorals'',<ref> Gillian Hughes, ''James Hogg: A Life'' (Edinburgh, 2007), 39.</ref> and several of his poems had been published separately in ''The Scots Magazine'' and ''The Edinburgh Magazine''.<ref>Gillian  H. Hughes, ''Hogg's Verse and Drama: A Chronological Listing'' (Stirling, 1990).</ref> For ''The Mountain Bard'' he revised his earlier texts, with input from [[Walter Scott]], making them more refined for a polite readership.<ref>Hughes, ''op. cit.'', 66\u201267; Valentina Bold, ''James Hogg: A Bard of Nature's Making'' (Oxford etc., 2007), 109.</ref> The first edition of ''The Mountain Bard'' contains  an introductory memoir and 21 poems, ten of them 'Ballads, in Imitation of the Antients', and the other eleven 'Songs Adapted to the Times' (though only seven of them are actually songs). The ballads are: \n*'Sir David Gr\u00e6me' (first published in ''[[The Scots Magazine]]'' in 1805) \n*'The Pedlar' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1804)\n*'Gilmanscleuch'\n*'The Fray of Elibank'\n*'Mess John'\n*'The Death of Douglas, Lord of Liddisdale' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1804)\n*'Willie Wilkin'\n*'Thirlestane: A Fragment'\n*'Lord Derwent: A Fragment'\n*'The Laird of Lairistan' \nThe poems in the second section are: \n*'Sandy Tod: A Scottish Pastoral' (first published in ''The Edinburgh Magazine'' in 1802)\n*'A Farewell to Ettrick' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1804 as 'Jamie's Farewell to Etttrick')\n*'Love Abused' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1805)\n*'Epistle to Mr T. M. C., London' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1805)\n*'Scotia's Glens'\n*'Donald Macdonald' (first published as a song-sheet probably in 1803)<ref>Gilbert, ''op. cit'', 454.</ref>\n*'The Author's Address to his Auld Dog Hector' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1805 as 'A Shepherd's Address to his Auld Dog Hector')\n*'The Bonnets o' Bonny Dundee' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1804)\n*'Auld Ettrick John' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1804)\n*'The Hay Making' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1805)\n*'Bonny Jean' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1803)\n\n===The third edition===\nThere was no second edition of ''The Mountain Bard'', but the first edition appeared in two formats. The third edition was published in Edinburgh on 19 February 1821 by Oliver & Boyd as ''The Mountain Bard; consisting of Legendary Ballads and Tales''.<ref>Hughes, ''op. cit.'', 174.</ref> Hogg provided the volume, which he intended to form part of a Collected Works, with an extended, updated version of the memoir. He retained the ten ballads from the first edition and (concluding the volume) three of the poems from its second section, with revisions again often in the direction of refinement:<ref>Bold, ''op. cit.'', 108\u201215.</ref>\n*'Sandy Tod: A Scottish Pastoral'\n*'Farewell to Ettrick'\n*'The Author's Address to his Auld Dog Hector'\nBefore this concluding trio Hogg inserted four poems not included in the 1807 edition:\n*'The Wife of Crowle' (first published in Hogg's periodical ''The Spy'' in 1810 as 'A Fragment')\n*'The Lairde of Kirkmabreeke' (a ballad satirical of medieval chivalry)\n*'The Tweeddale Raide' (a ballad by Robert Hogg, James's nephew)\n*'Robin an' Nanny' (a very early rural ballad)\nWith the exception of 'Epistle to Mr T. M. C., London' the remaining poems from the second section of the 1807 edition had been included in ''The Forest Minstrel'' (1810), and most of them reappeared in ''Songs by the Ettrick Shepherd'' (1831).\n\n===Standard critical edition===\nThe standard modern critical edition, by Suzanne Gilbert (2007), occupies a volume in the Stirling/South Carolina Research Edition of The Collected Works of James Hogg, published by Edinburgh University Press.\n\n==Reception==\nThe 1807 edition received nine reviews.<ref>The reviews are listed by Gilbert, ''op. cit.'', lxviii.</ref> In general the critics were well-disposed to Hogg as a rustic genius like [[Robert Burns]]. Typical is ''The Poetical Register'': 'Mr. Hogg is the poet of the Shepherds; and is really an honour to them. Shepherds, be it remembered, were always a poetical tribe. The Ballads of Mr. Hogg are in the true style of that sort of writing. They are simple and natural, and contain many spirited and picturesque ideas and descriptions, and, occasionally, strokes of genuine humour. The songs also are good.'<ref>''The Poetical Register'', 6 (1807), 549.</ref> The reviews of the 1821 volume<ref>Eight of the reviews are listed by Gilbert, ''op. cit.'', lxviii.</ref> were mostly much less favourable than those of the first edition, Hogg's expanded memoir with its disconcertingly frank account of his experience of literary Edinburgh coming in for particular adverse criticism from the Scottish periodicals.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Scottish literature]]\n[[Category: Ballads]]\n[[Category:Works by James Hogg]]\n", "text_old": "'''The Mountain Bard''' (1807), containing 21 poems, was [[James Hogg]]'s first substantial poetical publication.\n\n==Editions==\n===The first edition===\n''The Mountain Bard; consisting of Ballads and Songs, founded on facts and legendary tales. By James Hogg, The Ettrick Shepherd'' was first published in Edinburgh in February 1807 by [[Archibald Constable]] and Co. and in London by [[John Murray]].<ref>James Hogg, ''The Mountain Bard'', ed. Suzanne Gilbert (Edinburgh, 2007), xli. </ref> Hogg had had seven poems printed privately in 1801 as ''Scottish Pastorals'',<ref> Gillian Hughes, ''James Hogg: A Life'' (Edinburgh, 2007), 39.</ref> and several of his poems had been published separately in ''The Scots Magazine'' and ''The Edinburgh Magazine''.<ref>Gillian  H. Hughes, ''Hogg's Verse and Drama: A Chronological Listing'' (Stirling, 1990).</ref> For ''The Mountain Bard'' he revised his earlier texts, with input from [[Walter Scott]], making them more refined for a polite readership.<ref>Hughes, ''op. cit.'', 66\u201267; Valentina Bold, ''James Hogg: A Bard of Nature's Making'' (Oxford etc., 2007), 109.</ref> The first edition of ''The Mountain Bard'' contains  an introductory memoir and 21 poems, ten of them 'Ballads, in Imitation of the Antients', and the other eleven 'Songs Adapted to the Times' (though only seven of them are actually songs). The ballads are: \n*'Sir David Gr\u00e6me' (first published in ''[[The Scots Magazine]]'' in 1805) \n*'The Pedlar' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1804)\n*'Gilmanscleuch'\n*'The Fray of Elibank'\n*'Mess John'\n*'The Death of Douglas, Lord of Liddisdale' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1804)\n*'Willie Wilkin'\n*'Thirlestane: A Fragment'\n*'Lord Derwent: A Fragment'\n*'The Laird of Lairistan' \nThe poems in the second section are: \n*'Sandy Tod: A Scottish Pastoral' (first published in ''The Edinburgh Magazine'' in 1802)\n*'A Farewell to Ettrick' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1804 as 'Jamie's Farewell to Etttrick')\n*'Love Abused' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1805)\n*'Epistle to Mr T. M. C., London' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1805)\n*'Scotia's Glens'\n*'Donald Macdonald' (first published as a song-sheet probably in 1803)<ref>Gilbert, ''op. cit'', 454.</ref>\n*'The Author's Address to his Auld Dog Hector' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1805 as 'A Shepherd's Address to his Auld Dog Hector')\n*'The Bonnets o' Bonny Dundee' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1804)\n*'Auld Ettrick John' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1804)\n*'The Hay Making' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1805)\n*'Bonny Jean' (first published in ''The Scots Magazine'' in 1803)\n\n===The third edition===\nThere was no second edition of ''The Mountain Bard'', but the first edition appeared in two formats. The third edition was published in Edinburgh on 19 February 1821 by Oliver & Boyd as ''The Mountain Bard; consisting of Legendary Ballads and Tales''.<ref>Hughes, ''op. cit.'', 174.</ref> Hogg provided the volume, which he intended to form part of a Collected Works, with an extended, updated version of the memoir. He retained the ten ballads from the first edition and (concluding the volume) three of the poems from its second section, with revisions again often in the direction of refinement:<ref>Bold, ''op. cit.'', 108\u201215.</ref>\n*'Sandy Tod: A Scottish Pastoral'\n*'Farewell to Ettrick'\n*'The Author's Address to his Auld Dog Hector'\nBefore this concluding trio Hogg inserted four poems not included in the 1807 edition:\n*'The Wife of Crowle' (first published in Hogg's periodical ''The Spy'' in 1810 as 'A Fragment')\n*'The Lairde of Kirkmabreeke' (a ballad satirical of medieval chivalry)\n*'The Tweeddale Raide' (a ballad by Robert Hogg, James's nephew)\n*'Robin an' Nanny' (a very early rural ballad)\nWith the exception of 'Epistle to Mr T. M. C., London' the remaining poems from the second section of the 1807 edition had been included in ''The Forest Minstrel'' (1810), and most of them reappeared in ''Songs by the Ettrick Shepherd'' (1831).\n\n===Standard critical edition===\nThe standard modern critical edition, by Suzanne Gilbert (2007), occupies a volume in the Stirling/South Carolina Research Edition of The Collected Works of James Hogg, published by Edinburgh University Press.\n\n==Reception==\nThe 1807 edition received nine reviews.<ref>The reviews are listed by Gilbert, ''op. cit.'', lxviii.</ref> In general the critics were well-disposed to Hogg as a rustic genius like [[Robert Burns]]. Typical is ''The Poetical Register'': 'Mr. Hogg is the poet of the Shepherds; and is really an honour to them. Shepherds, be it remembered, were always a poetical tribe. The Ballads of Mr. Hogg are in the true style of that sort of writing. They are simple and natural, and contain many spirited and picturesque ideas and descriptions, and, occasionally, strokes of genuine humour. The songs also are good.'<ref>''The Poetical Register'', 6 (1807), 549.</ref> The reviews of the 1821 volume<ref>Eight of the reviews are listed by Gilbert, ''op. cit.'', lxviii.</ref> were mostly much less favourable than those of the first edition, Hogg's expanded memoir with its disconcertingly frank account of his experience of literary Edinburgh coming in for particular adverse criticism from the Scottish periodicals.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Scottish literature]]\n[[Category: Ballads]]\n[[Category:Works by James Hogg]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJohn Murray(link changed toJohn Murray (publisher)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Mountain_Bard"}
